Re: How to read 小火
by NileCat » Thu 04.14.2011 2:00 pm In English, you use the same word “fire” for both the intentionally made fire and the accidentally occurred fire, right?In Japanese, 火 means fire in general as well. But fire accidents such as burning houses are called 火事. But only 火 doesn’t mean 火事 in most cases.So, “small fire” can be translated either 小さな火 or 小さな火事. The former can be a small fire of a candle or something. And the latter means a small fire accident. (Something like “only the kitchen was burned down and the rest of the house was fine”)Originally:ぼや＝small fire <accident>小火=しょうか=小さな火=small fire<in general>The origin of the word ぼやis uncertain. There seem a couple of different theories. But somewhere down the line, they started to render it using the kanji 小火. Because…it was just handy. (It’s much shorter than “小さな火事”, isn’t it?)Then, nowadays, 小火（ぼや）is very commonly used whereas 小火（しょうか）is seldom used. （For some reason, we call them 小さな火）Yes, this is ateji.Do you see the concept of this phrase? :「本気と書いてマジと読む」（ほんきとかいてまじとよむ）“Maji” is a slang based on the word “majime（真面目）” which also means serious. I mean it! = 本気だよ！ほんきだよ！= マジだよ！Therefore: 本気（マジ）だよ！ became “popular”.
NileCat
